<paragraph id="E97036DD3F76FFE1FF76F80CFD1CF844" blockId="67.[151,1437,1930,2028]" box="[151,764,1930,1957]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">
Size. Maximum size 
<quantity id="2E379B383F76FFE1FE65F80CFE30F845" box="[388,464,1930,1957]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.5" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" unit="cm" value="9.5">9.5 cm</quantity>
total length (Miller 1986).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1D565563F76FFE6FF26F828FE28FE17" lastPageId="68" lastPageNumber="69" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" type="description">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F76FFE1FF26F828FA7DF80D" blockId="67.[151,1437,1930,2028]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">
Morphology. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F76FFE1FEBFF828FD7AF829" bold="true" box="[350,666,1965,1992]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">D VI + I,15; A I,16–17; P 22</emphasis>
(Miller 1986). Moderately large goby with high, laterally compressed and robust body, head high and moderately large. Snout large and blunt. Eyes dorsolateral, interorbital space narrow.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F71FFE6FF76FF11FBCEFF18" blockId="68.[151,1437,150,502]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">
Caudal peduncle deep, almost same depth as body. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F71FFE6FD3DFF11FDDBFF34" bold="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">The first dorsal fin with elongated spines, third and fourth spine longest. Caudal fin lanceolate.</emphasis>
Predorsal area and nape scaled. Scales large, visible on freshly dead specimens on body and usually also on predorsal area, visibility on live specimens unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F71FFE6FF26FE85FAFFFEA3" blockId="68.[151,1437,150,502]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">
Freshly dead coloration. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F71FFE6FE0AFE85FA7CFEFC" bold="true" box="[491,1436,258,285]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Body fawn, with diffuse vertical yellow and dark brown bands across body.</emphasis>
Margins of anal and caudal fins with a blackish shade (
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F71FFE6FD1EFEA1FCB3FEA3" box="[767,851,295,322]" captionStart="FIGURE 60" captionStartId="68.[151,250,1264,1288]" captionTargetBox="[177,1410,525,1240]" captionTargetId="figure-171@68.[177,1410,525,1240]" captionTargetPageId="68" captionText="FIGURE 60. Freshly dead coloration of Lesueurigobius sanzi. Photo by A. Kassar, Beni Saf, Alboran Sea, Algeria." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601751" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601751/files/figure.png" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Fig. 60</figureCitation>
); live coloration unknown (Miller 1986).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F71FFE6FF26FECDFD07FE84" blockId="68.[151,1437,150,502]" box="[199,743,331,357]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">
Similar species. 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F71FFE6FE9EFECDFD94FE84" authorityName="Benthic" baseAuthorityName="Malm" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[383,628,331,357]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Lesueurigobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="friesii">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F71FFE6FE9EFECDFD94FE84" box="[383,628,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Lesueurigobius friesii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F71FFE6FD63FECDFD00FE85" authorityName="Benthic" baseAuthorityName="Risso" baseAuthorityYear="1810" box="[642,736,331,357]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Lesueurigobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="suerii">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F71FFE6FD63FECDFD72FE85" box="[642,658,331,356]" italics="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">L</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F71FFE6FD41FECDFD00FE85" box="[672,736,331,356]" italics="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">suerii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F71FFE6FF26FEE9FAFBFE6B" blockId="68.[151,1437,150,502]" box="[199,1307,367,394]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">
Habitat. Circalittoral species, known from 
<quantity id="2E379B383F71FFE6FD44FEE9FCF6FE68" box="[677,790,367,393]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.35" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="4.7" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" unit="m" value="73.5" valueMax="100.0" valueMin="47.0">47–100 m</quantity>
on soft bottoms, sand and mud (Miller 1986).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F71FFE6FF26FE15FE28FE17" blockId="68.[151,1437,150,502]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">
Geographic distribution. Atlantic Ocean and adjacent Mediterranean: known from the eastern Atlantic coast from 
<collectingCountry id="91D8764D3F71FFE6FF35FE31FED3FE30" box="[212,307,439,465]" name="Portugal" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Portugal</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry id="91D8764D3F71FFE6FEB4FE31FE30FE30" box="[341,464,439,465]" name="Mauritania" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Mauritania</collectingCountry>
(Miller 1986) and also off northern 
<collectingCountry id="91D8764D3F71FFE6FC81FE31FC24FE30" box="[864,964,439,465]" name="Namibia" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Namibia</collectingCountry>
. In the Mediterranean it is known from the Alboran Sea (Miller 1986).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
